[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'So I already did a video on OSINT a&nbsp; while back. Decent video, solid tools,&nbsp;&nbsp; did its job. But since then I\'ve gone way&nbsp; deeper into this rabbit hole and learned tricks&nbsp;&nbsp; that genuinely made me sit back in my chair like&nbsp; there\'s no way this is legal to know. So tonight&nbsp;&nbsp; I\'m dropping everything I\'ve found since then'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the stuff nobody else is sharing, the&nbsp; actual FBI type shi, tools that make&nbsp;&nbsp; Maltego and Shodan look like the&nbsp; beginner tier they actually are. Quick reality check before anything else.&nbsp; Everything here uses public information.&nbsp;&nbsp; No breaching, no hacking, no unauthorized&nbsp; access. The reason this matters as much as&nbsp;&nbsp; it does is because almost nobody understands&nbsp; how much of their life is sitting in public,&nbsp;&nbsp; searchable, cross-referenceable places.&nbsp; Understanding these tools is how investigators&nbsp;&nbsp; find people. It\'s also exactly how you&nbsp; find out what\'s findable about yourself. Let\'s start with something most people sleep on&nbsp; completely, Pipl and Spokeo are fine for surface&nbsp;&nbsp; level stuff but the real professionals reach for&nbsp; something called IntelTechniques, built by Michael&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Bazzell, a former FBI cyber crimes investigator&nbsp; who now runs the most respected OSINT training&nbsp;&nbsp; operation in the field. His site has a free search&nbsp; tool collection that aggregates dozens of lookups&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'into one place, usernames, emails, phone numbers,&nbsp; all cross-referenced instantly. This is the same&nbsp;&nbsp; methodology actual federal investigators are&nbsp; trained on, available to you for free, right now.'

[00:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Now let\'s talk about something that will genuinely&nbsp; blow your mind, Epieos. You give it an email&nbsp;&nbsp; address and it tells you which Google services&nbsp; that email is tied to, whether there\'s a profile&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'photo associated with it, sometimes even a real&nbsp; name pulled straight from Google\'s own systems.&nbsp;&nbsp; People think their email is anonymous. Epieos will&nbsp; frequently prove otherwise in about four seconds.'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Sherlock is the next one and if you\'ve never used&nbsp; it, prepare to lose an evening. You give Sherlock&nbsp;&nbsp; a single username and it checks that exact&nbsp; username against over four hundred websites&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'simultaneously to tell you everywhere that&nbsp; name has an account. Someone uses the same&nbsp;&nbsp; username on their throwaway Reddit and their&nbsp; real Instagram? Sherlock just connected them.&nbsp;&nbsp; Run it from any terminal, `python3 sherlock.py&nbsp; username`, and watch the results populate in&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'real time. This is genuinely one of the most&nbsp; underrated tools in the entire OSINT space. Then there\'s Holehe, which does something&nbsp; similarly unsettling but with emails instead&nbsp;&nbsp; of usernames. Feed it an email and it silently&nbsp; checks that address against over a hundred&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'platforms to see which ones it\'s registered on,&nbsp; without sending a single password reset email,&nbsp;&nbsp; without alerting anyone. It works by&nbsp; exploiting subtle differences in how&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'registration pages respond to existing versus&nbsp; nonexistent accounts. One email address in,&nbsp;&nbsp; and thirty seconds later you have a partial&nbsp; map of someone\'s entire digital footprint. Now here\'s where it gets genuinely federal level.&nbsp; GrayKey and Cellebrite are the actual tools law&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'enforcement uses to extract data from seized&nbsp; phones, but the public-facing equivalent that&nbsp;&nbsp; regular researchers can access is something called&nbsp; Cellebrite\'s own published methodology documents,&nbsp;&nbsp; and more practically, Hunchly, a browser extension&nbsp; built specifically for investigators that&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'automatically captures and timestamps every single&nbsp; page you visit during an investigation, building a&nbsp;&nbsp; fully documented evidence trail as you browse.&nbsp; Real investigators use this so that everything&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'they find is admissible and reconstructable later.&nbsp; Most OSINT hobbyists have never even heard of it. For geolocation, forget basic reverse&nbsp; image search for a second and look at&nbsp;&nbsp; something called Overpass Turbo combined&nbsp; with OpenStreetMap data. Investigators&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'use this to cross-reference visual landmarks&nbsp; in a photo, a specific style of streetlight,&nbsp;&nbsp; a particular road marking, an unusual building&nbsp; shape, against actual geographic databases to&nbsp;&nbsp; pin down a location with shocking&nbsp; precision. This is exactly the kind&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of technique Bellingcat uses to geolocate&nbsp; conflict footage down to the exact street. SpiderFoot deserves a mention here too&nbsp; because it automates almost everything&nbsp;&nbsp; I just described into a single scan.&nbsp; Point it at a domain, an email, or an IP,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and it pulls from dozens of data sources&nbsp; simultaneously, including breach databases,&nbsp;&nbsp; building a full relationship map&nbsp; automatically. It\'s open source,&nbsp;&nbsp; it runs locally, and most people who\'ve heard&nbsp; the name still have never actually run it.'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'And then there\'s something most&nbsp; OSINT content completely ignores,&nbsp;&nbsp; court records and public filing databases.&nbsp; PACER for federal court records in the US,&nbsp;&nbsp; and equivalent public registries in most&nbsp; other countries, contain an enormous amount&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'of information that nobody thinks to check.&nbsp; Lawsuits, property disputes, business filings,&nbsp;&nbsp; all public, all searchable, and frequently&nbsp; containing addresses, employment history,&nbsp;&nbsp; and financial details that no social&nbsp; media platform will ever give you.'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'None of these tools are illegal. None of them&nbsp; are hacking. Every single one works because&nbsp;&nbsp; the information was already public, posted, filed,&nbsp; registered, or leaked into a breach database that&nbsp;&nbsp; anyone can search. The skill in OSINT isn\'t&nbsp; accessing secret information. It\'s knowing&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'that the information was never secret to begin&nbsp; with, and knowing exactly where to look for it. This is also exactly why I built a full&nbsp; OSINT course inside Cyberflow Academy,&nbsp;&nbsp; because the tools I just listed are&nbsp; genuinely scattered across forums,&nbsp;&nbsp; GitHub repos, and obscure training pages&nbsp; that ninety percent of people learning&nbsp;&nbsp; OSINT never find on their own. The course goes&nbsp; through this entire methodology, the tools,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'the actual investigative workflow professionals&nbsp; use, how to chain findings together instead of&nbsp;&nbsp; just running tools in isolation, and&nbsp; the community inside is full of people&nbsp;&nbsp; actively doing this, cross-referencing findings,&nbsp; helping each other when a lead goes cold. Link\'s&nbsp;&nbsp; in the description, code Cyber50 for fifty&nbsp; percent off. Now let\'s wrap this up properly.'
